    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output="The provided prospectus excerpts disclose several specific restrictions and limitations on shareholders' ability to sell or transfer shares. These fall into three main categories: **lock-up agreements tied to the IPO**, **automatic conversion triggers for Class B common stock**, and certain **exceptions** (including directed shares and permitted transfers). No right of first refusal is mentioned.\n\n### 1. Lock‑Up Restrictions (Post‑IPO Holding Periods)\n\n**Two‑tiered lock‑up regime:**\n- **366‑day lock‑up** – Applies to the **Founder and certain significant investors**.  \n  - Covers an aggregate number of shares (including 100% of the Founder’s shares).  \n  - These shares **are not subject to any early release provisions**. The Founder is explicitly excluded from all early release mechanisms.\n- **180‑day lock‑up** – Applies to **all other remaining shareholders** (other shares of common stock and convertible securities) under various agreements.\n\n**Prohibited activities during the lock‑up period** (without prior written consent of Goldman Sachs & Co. LLC on behalf of the underwriters):\n- Sell, offer, contract to sell, pledge, grant any option, right or warrant to purchase, lend, or otherwise transfer or dispose of (directly or indirectly) any **lock‑up securities**.\n- Engage in hedging or derivative transactions (short sales, puts, calls, forwards, swaps, etc.) that transfer economic consequences of ownership.\n- Make any demand for or exercise any registration rights with respect to lock‑up securities.\n- Publicly announce an intention to do any of the above.\n\n**Definition of “lock‑up securities”** – includes common stock, options, rights, warrants, and any securities convertible into or exchangeable for common stock, whether now owned or later acquired.\n\n**Early release schedule for a subset of 180‑day and 366‑day shares** (only for shares designated as “Early Release Eligible Shares”; Founder’s shares are not part of this):\n- 20% on the second trading day after **quarterly earnings for June\u202f30,\u202f2026** are released.\n- An additional 10% if the stock price is ≥30% above the IPO price for at least 5 of the last 10 trading days ending on that earnings date.\n- An additional 7% on each of **70, 90, 105, 120, and 135 days** after the offering.\n- An additional 28% after the **September\u202f30,\u202f2026** quarterly earnings release.\n- All remaining Early Release Eligible Shares may be transferred after **180 days** from the offering.\n\n### 2. Exceptions to Lock‑Up Restrictions\n\n- **Mergers & acquisitions** – Lock‑up restrictions do **not** apply to securities issued by the Company in connection with mergers, acquisitions, or similar transactions during the lock‑up period.\n- **Directed share program** – Shares reserved for employees and certain other individuals designated by management are **not subject to any lock‑up restriction**. The prospectus states: “If purchased by these persons, these shares of Class\u202fA common stock will not be subject to a lock‑up restriction.”\n- Additional exceptions will be detailed in a later amendment to the registration statement.\n\n### 3. Transfer Restrictions on Class\u202fB Common Stock (Voting Power Preservation)\n\nBeyond the lock‑up period, Class\u202fB common stock carries a separate, permanent transfer restriction designed to prevent loss of super‑voting control:\n\n- Any **Transfer** (broadly defined – sale, assignment, pledge, gift, hypothecation, transfer of voting control by proxy, etc., whether voluntary or involuntary) of a Class\u202fB share automatically **converts it into one share of Class\u202fA common stock**.\n- **Permitted transfers** that do **not** trigger conversion are strictly enumerated: transfers among registered holders of Class\u202fB, natural persons who transferred shares/equity awards to certain “permitted entities,” family members, certain family trusts, partnerships, LLCs, corporations owned by qualified shareholders, charitable trusts, retirement accounts, and transfers for estate/succession planning.  \n- Only Mr. Musk, his family members, and certain entities permitted under the charter may receive newly issued Class\u202fB shares in the future.\n\n### 4. Other Relevant Disclosures\n\n- After the lock‑up periods expire, shares become eligible for sale under **Rule\u202f144** (subject to volume, holding period, and manner‑of‑sale requirements) or via **registration rights** held by certain investors.\n- The prospectus repeatedly warns that future resales by Mr. Musk or other existing shareholders could significantly depress the stock price.\n\n**Summary:** The document details extensive lock‑up restrictions (366 days for the Founder with no early release, 180 days for others with a staggered early release schedule), prohibitions on hedging and derivative transactions during those periods, and a permanent conversion‑on‑transfer mechanism for Class\u202fB shares to preserve voting control, with a narrow list of permitted transfers. A right of first refusal is not disclosed.",
